        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Augustus Ca[e]sar pacificus.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Augustus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The peace-making Caesar Augustus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>2. Numa[e] historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The royal history of Numa.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Astute Senatus cedendo pra[e]it, et superat superatus. Nec populus tam impotenter potens, ( quàm posteà. Posse, et nolle quod erat nobilium, magis nobile, vel in plebe ignobili. Ita Senatus, specie inferior, re potentior. Ut sa[e]pè i[nfr]a.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The Senate leads cleverly by yielding, and triumphs after being defeated. Not even the people is so feebly powerful as later. To have power over that what belongs to noblemen, and not to desire it, is more than noble, even in the undistinguished common people.
               In this way the Senate is weaker in appearance, but more powerful in practice. As often below.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Quantùm Fortuna inualuerat in philosophi Numa[e] regno, peritè Plutarchus, ac profundè in suo singulari tractatu de fortuna Romanoru[m].
                        .</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Plutarch"/>
                    <book title="Moralia"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>How strong Fortuna was in the reign of the philosopher Numa is skilfully and thoroughly related by Plutarch in his remarkable treatise about the fortune of the Romans.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>i[nfr]a, 103.</marginalia_text>
                    <internal_ref>
