        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Techna hypocritica. Sic Euander venerabilis miraculo rei noua[e]. s[upr]a /
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Evander"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000027" text="s[upr]a"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The art of pretending. Thus also the august Evander through the miracle of a new development. See above.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Janus, bis clausus Roma[e], post regnum Numa[e]. Ciuitas, semper in armis: ex consilio Romuli, et compendio suo: altero quasi diuino Oraculo; altero certè humano, serioq[ue] argumento. Thaumaturgia, magnum religionis mysterium; 
                        et sola Diuinitatis demonstratio. Vndè nuga[e], omnium Religionum ostenta, ad Hebra[e]orum, et Christianorum miracula. Eccè Deus in Biblijs: Heros in poetis: vir in Romanis Historijs: quibus nihil humanum fortius, aut prudentius.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Janus"/>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <book title="Bible"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Janus was closed twice in Rome after Numa’s reign. The city was always armed, owing to Romulus’ strategy and to his profitable approach, in the case of the former as through some divine oracle, and in the case of the latter certainly by a human and
                earnest argument. Miracle-working, a great mystery of religion and the only demonstration of divine power. From which came the nonsense and portents of all religions up to the miracles of the Hebrews and the Christians. Look: God in the Bible, the hero in the poets, 
                the man in Roman History – no human action is braver or more sagacious than these.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
